Yes, you had stated exactly that previously and I pointed out the same thing you noticed. We come to conclusions in the opposite way. I research facts and verifiable data then make a conclusion and decide how I feel about it. You decide what is true based on how you feel about it, then seek out facts that might support this or ignore those that refute your &quot;feeling&quot;. This makes me a proponent of scientific method, reason and logic and you a proponent of faith, feeling and intuition. Your choice, but not very effective in the real world where researching medicines, using engineering principles to build things, etc. is necessary, but like I said--your choice.<br>
<br>
&quot;so i may need some proof as to why this statement from Leviathan is true...&quot;<br>
As I stated, I do not agree with everything in Leviathan, but referred only to the social contract. You are getting at the heart of this argument though and despite the fact I disagree with Hobbes on some things and cannot support all his statements, I'll give this a try. I think I know what he's saying.<br>
<br>
Hobbes says, &quot;For as to the strength of body, the weakest has strength enough to kill the strongest, either by secret machination or by confederacy with others that are in the same danger with himself&quot;<br>
<br>
dag retorts, &quot;this simply isn't true when it comes to the mentally handicapped. if i'm reading this correctly then he is saying the weakest mentally handicapped born without limbs has the power to kill the strongest hitler. survival of the fittest would argue that they should die off first leaving behind the strongest which frusterates celestial law.&quot;<br>
He is not necessarily speaking of mental illness, though his qualification that the killing could be done &quot;by secret machination or by confederacy with others&quot; takes care of this. For the record, Hitler was nuts and not that bright--though many of those around him were smart, but evil. If you mean could a retarded person kill a person of average IQ...with a &quot;secret machination&quot; or gun or knife why not? Most mentally retarded folks are not so handicapped as to not be able to pull a trigger and many would be able to get help from the physically able.<br>
As for frustrating celestial law. Again, celestial law is an LDS term so it doesn't have anything to do with Hobbes' arguments, but it seems you are saying if a weak human kills a strong one this goes against evolution. Goodness sakes, yes there is a great deal of this already going on is there not? Do you suppose all murders are the strong and genetically more &quot;fit&quot; killing the weakest? The advances in technology and manipulation of the environment humans have accomplished puts a sort of stall on evolution for now (this is not agreed upon by all evolutionists), but what often causes a &quot;survival of the fittest&quot; situation is the chagning environment, which we as humans now largely control. We can heat and cool our homes for example, fabricate coverings for our bodies, grow more than enough food and are at the top of the food chain. If anything, we are depleting our own resources and to make things more interesting what makes a male attractive as a mate may not have changed deep in our brains (women still find more masculine faces more attractive at certain points in our menstrual cycles) our societal and behavioral conditioning prohibit us from mating with them and often drive us toward more intellectual or financially successful mates. I.E., it ain't the brawniest that can best provide for our offspring anymore...aka the Bill Gates/Dilbert phenomenon we hear so much about.<br>
<br>
Anyway--I can see how there might be exceptions to Hobbes' assertion in an abstract sense, but his main point that in a society with no contracts or constraints the strongest is not even safe still holds. There are many cases of mentally, physically, financially strong folks being taken down with weapons that level the playing field (9/11) or the weaker members of society banning together (French Revolution).<br>
<br>
