<br>
1.Columbus was not seeking to prove the earth was round. He was attempting to find the lands that Marco Polo had to China a few hundred years before. It was about trade and exploration, not following god’s spirit. Finding a route through the Caribbean islands and bumping into North America was a boo-boo, not a confirmation of some spiritual message.<br>
<br>
2.The people of his time WANTED a new route to replace the passage now blocked with the fall of Constantinople to the Muslims. They wanted to purchase asian products directly, not through the Muslims at the places they still could. It was a race dag---spoils to the winner and that’s why some royalty was ecstatic to provide the dough.<br>
3.Columbus’ voyages proved his theories/feelings/ideas TOTALLY WRONG. He based them on texts as old as the 2nd Century (yup, that’s right, men had figured the earth was round waaaaaaaaay before Columbus and he borrowed the idea from them, not the holy spirit). To quote one author, “Columbus founded his theory on two mistaken propositions—that the Asian continent stretched much farther to the east than it actually does, and that Japan lay about 2,400 km (about 1,500 mi) east of the Asian mainland. Columbus also greatly underestimated the circumference of the earth. Columbus calculated that the Canary Islands lay only about 4,440 km (about 2,760 mi) from Japan; the actual distance is about 19,000 km (about 12,000 mi). Similar errors were made by other learned men of the time, including the Florentine geographer Paulo de Pozzo Toscanelli, with whom Columbus may have corresponded. Neither Columbus nor anyone else in Europe suspected that two vast continents lay in the way of a westward passage to Asia.”<br>
<br>
4.Even after reaching the new lands and all that happened with settlements, Columbus was so convinced he HAD reached Asia after all, he led no less than 3 more expeditions to the Caribbean. No holy spirit help there and he naturally failed yet again.<br>
<br>
5.Columbus was a vain men very concerned with status and wealth and was rewarded for his finds. He may have been brave, but it was nothing holy nor higher purpose in his travels…it was about fame, money and status and if a few thousand Natives were slaughtered and/or enslaved as a result, well so be it.<br>
<br>
6.Columbus WAS NOT the first one to reach North America—the Vikings were. They were not following the HF either.<br>
<br>
None of this is “feelings” and just because every minute of his life is not recorded on a camcorder does not mean it is equally valid with your baseless claims he was guided by a spirit. I dare say one of your leaders born well after these events thought this little gem up and has fortunately not spread it around much or folks might have some rather alarming revelations about the LDS church. <br>
<br>
Please tell me this is not the crap being fed to LDS kids!! Other Mormons---you don't also believe this and other wacky claims with no foundation from history do you? Is this one man's creation or something regularly taught small children?<br>
<br>
Any other areas of history you care to twist beyond recognition in contradiction to the facts and evidence? Sorry but doing this to history is my pet peeve.<br>
<br>
